'''''Coburg''''' was a fishing trawler that was built in 1938 and requisitoned by the [[Kriegsmarine]] in 1940. Converted to a [[weather ship]], she became trapped in ice off the east coast of Greenland in October 1943 and was abandoned in June 1944.
==Decsription== ''Coburg'' was {{convert|135|ft|8|in|m|2|disp=flip}} long with a beam of {{convert|25|ft|3|in|m|2|disp=flip}}. She had a depth of {{convert|9|ft|9|in|m|2|disp=flip}}. She was powered by a 6-cylinder [[four stroke engine|four-stroke single cycle single action]] [[diesel engine]] rated at 120 [[nominal horsepower|nhp]]. It drove a single screw propeller, which gave the vessel a speed of {{convert|11.5|kn|km/h}}. The engine was built by [[MAN SE|Maschinenfabriek Augsburg-Nürnburg]] [[Aktiengesellschaft|AG]], [[Augsburg]].<ref name=C39/><ref name=miramar>{{csr|register=MSI|id=5614885 |shipname=Coburg |accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref>
==History== ''Coburg'' was built as [[yard number]] 125 in 1938 by Schulte & Bruns, [[Emden]] for H Bischoff & Co, [[Bremen]], Germany.<ref name=C39>{{cite web |url=http://www.plimsollshipdata.org/pdffile.php?name=39a0172.pdf |title=Lloyd's Register, Steamers & Motorships under 300 tons, Trawlers &c. |author=Lloyd's of London |year=1939 |publisher=Plimsoll Ship Data |accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=Coburg>{{cite web |url=http://www.warcovers.dk/greenland/wbs2.htm |title=Wetterbeobachtungs-Schiff Coburg WBS 2 |publisher=Warcovers |accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=miramar/> She was completed in August 1938.<ref name=miramar/> Her port of registry was [[Wesermünde]] and the [[Code Letters]] DFDX were allocated.<ref name=C39/>
''Coburg'' was requisitioned by the [[Kriegsmarine]] in 1940 and converted to a [[weather ship]]. She was commissioned on 3 August as ''WBS 2 Coburg''. She had a complement of eighteen plus eight meteorologists.<ref name=Coburg/>
On 15 March 1943, ''Coburg'' sailed from [[Hammerfest]], Norway escorted by {{GS|U-657||2}}. Her mission was to establish a new automatic weather station on [[Bear Island (Norway)|Bear Island]].<ref name=Coburg/> On 28 August, she sailed from [[Narvik]] as part of the Bassgeiger Expedition. She became trapped by ice off the [[Île-de-France (Greenland)|Île-de-France]], Greenland, eventually making landfall at Cape Sussi, [[Shannon Island]] on 16 October. {{USCGC |Northland|WPG-49|6}} failed to spot the ship. Her crew spent the winter in snow caves, with supplies being dropped to them by air. In November or December 1943, the Danish ''[[Slædepatruljen Sirius]]'' discovered the camp, but were unable to mount an attack at the time. An attack on 22 April 1944 was unsuccessful, although one German was killed. On 3 June, ''Coburg'' was scuttled and abandoned. The camp was evacuated by [[Junkers Ju 290]] aircraft of 2 ''Staffeln'', ''Fernaufklärungsgruppe'' 5 and the personnel returned to [[Trondheim]], Norway.<ref name=miramar/><ref name=Bassgeiger>{{cite web |url=http://www.warcovers.dk/greenland/bassgeiger_member.htm |title=Bassgeiger German Weather Party |publisher=Warcovers |accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=FAG5>{{cite web |url=http://www.warcovers.dk/greenland/fag5.htm |title=Fernauklärungs-Gruppe 5 |publisher=Warcovers |accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref> The burnt out wreck of ''Coburg'' was discovered on 24 July 1944 by USCGC ''Northland''. Her crew destroyed the weather station.<ref name=Northland>{{cite DANFS | title = Northland | url = http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/guard/wpg49.htm | accessdate = 18 February 2015 }}</ref><ref name=Cutter>{{cite web |url=http://www.jacksjoint.com/cutter_northland_at_war.htm |title=The Cutter Northland At War |first=Jack |last=Dorsey |publisher= The Virginian-Pilot |accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref>
